WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.332
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:10.270
IMOGEN HEAP: Hi, guys, very
nice to be here on the stage,

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:13.190
happy to share whatever
you want to ask me,

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:15.800
and I actually spent a bit of
time up in the creative labs

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:17.850
one day and just saw
some amazing things.

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.850
So if it's anyone in here
that I might have met,

00:00:19.850 --> 00:00:22.353
hello again because I saw
lots of kind of music,

00:00:22.353 --> 00:00:24.020
cool little music
apps they were making.

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:25.080
And yeah, it was good.

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:25.970
BEN ARTHUR: Nice.

00:00:25.970 --> 00:00:28.190
So folks here in the
audience might know you

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:33.590
from songs that were licensed
for the "OC," or Zach Braff's

00:00:33.590 --> 00:00:36.890
"Garden State," or your
collaborations with Taylor

00:00:36.890 --> 00:00:38.570
Swift, or Ariana
Grande, or they might

00:00:38.570 --> 00:00:42.860
know about your performative
technology endeavor

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:43.830
in the Mi.Mu gloves.

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:45.800
They might have heard
about Creative Passport.

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:50.720
They might also have heard about
you doing the "Harry Potter

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:52.670
Cursed Child" soundtrack.

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:54.560
All of these things
are out there

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:58.550
in the world, which seems
breathtaking in their scope.

00:00:58.550 --> 00:01:02.150
How do you think about yourself
when you introduce yourself

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:04.031
at the allegorical party?

00:01:04.031 --> 00:01:05.239
How do you consider yourself?

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:06.575
What's your identity?

00:01:06.575 --> 00:01:07.700
IMOGEN HEAP: I don't know.

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:13.040
I just say, I enjoy
anything that kind of

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:15.440
is around the intersection
of music and tech.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:16.445
That's what I say.

00:01:16.445 --> 00:01:17.820
I don't go, like,
I'm a musician.

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:18.530
I'm a producer.

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:18.930
I'm a performer.

00:01:18.930 --> 00:01:19.520
I'm an engineer.

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:20.728
Hello, I've won some Grammys.

00:01:20.728 --> 00:01:22.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.140
I just go, I'm into
music and tech.

00:01:25.140 --> 00:01:26.640
BEN ARTHUR: I'm
into music and tech.

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:26.840
OK.

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:27.290
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah,
that's what I say.

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:28.920
BEN ARTHUR: So there's the
big umbrella that you--

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:29.030
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah.

00:01:29.030 --> 00:01:29.988
BEN ARTHUR: --consider.

00:01:29.988 --> 00:01:32.270
One of the things that
I've heard you reference

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:36.230
a couple of times, and it
seems almost contradictory

00:01:36.230 --> 00:01:40.820
to my image of you,
is only do what

00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:42.530
you can see in the headlights.

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:46.240
Can you talk about
what that means to you?

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:48.230
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah,
I would love to.

00:01:48.230 --> 00:01:51.500
Before the days of
Google search engine,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.090
we had a thing called Yahoo.

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:56.180
And one day, I was in the
studio, and I was making--

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:58.062
BEN ARTHUR: We'll
bleep that out.

00:01:58.062 --> 00:01:58.770
IMOGEN HEAP: Why?

00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:00.800
It is a nice story.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.920
And so I was there, kind
of going round and round

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:07.750
in circles trying
to finish this song.

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:09.000
So I am in my studio.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.450
That's the first time
I recorded a studio--

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:15.080
recorded an album on my own, so
I was in the studio constantly,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:18.417
all by myself, for a year, and
so it does send you a bit mad.

00:02:18.417 --> 00:02:20.750
And because I didn't have an
A and R man, or anyone that

00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:22.687
would come in and go,
oh, that's really good,

00:02:22.687 --> 00:02:24.520
or oh, you should turn
some more cowbell up,

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:28.430
or whatever they say, I
was going round and round.

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:29.890
And so I couldn't
finish his song,

00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:31.340
so I went onto
the search engine,

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:35.420
and I just said, how
do you write songs?

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:40.430
And I found this article
about this writer, novelist,

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:42.170
who had written
this little blog,

00:02:42.170 --> 00:02:45.320
and it said in it, only do what
you can see in the headlights.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.470
And what she meant
was, if in the song

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:51.140
you can see that there's a
hi-hat that needs fixing,

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:53.270
or you're trying
to finish a lyric,

00:02:53.270 --> 00:02:57.620
and you can see the colors of
his eyes, then just do that.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.430
Just write that bit, and
just keep chipping away.

00:03:01.430 --> 00:03:04.970
And eventually, you will see
the full path ahead of you,

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:07.790
and you'll see
all the landscape.

00:03:07.790 --> 00:03:10.510
But it's that kind, oh,
I've got so much to do.

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:13.550
I've got so much to do,
and it's overwhelming,

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:17.150
and you can't breathe, and
then you just remember, well,

00:03:17.150 --> 00:03:18.410
do what you can see now.

00:03:18.410 --> 00:03:19.500
Just do that.

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.470
Don't see, don't do all
that complicated stuff

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:22.270
that's far away.

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:24.020
You know you have to
get to it eventually,

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:25.993
but you can't see it just
yet, so just do that.

00:03:25.993 --> 00:03:26.910
So that's what I mean.

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:29.870
Yeah, and I use that a
lot in everything from,

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.030
like, how do I
look after my child

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:34.525
this morning when I've got
to get to this interview,

00:03:34.525 --> 00:03:35.150
and I've got--?

00:03:35.150 --> 00:03:36.525
You know, I just
say, do what you

00:03:36.525 --> 00:03:39.400
see in the headlights, which
is make sure she has breakfast,

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.300
and that's just, yeah,
it seems to be how I--

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:42.820
BEN ARTHUR: You are
supposed to feed them.

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:43.770
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah, I hear--

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:44.345
BEN ARTHUR: I'm a father--

00:03:44.345 --> 00:03:44.600
IMOGEN HEAP: I do hear that.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:45.140
BEN ARTHUR: --so I know.

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:46.160
IMOGEN HEAP: For six
months, I didn't feed her.

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:47.000
BEN ARTHUR: Every meal--

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.515
you're not allowed
to skip even one.

00:03:48.515 --> 00:03:48.710
IMOGEN HEAP: No.

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:49.210
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:49.210 --> 00:03:50.980
No, it's true.

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:52.970
BEN ARTHUR: It's
very strict rules.

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:57.020
So one of the many things
that you've juggled

00:03:57.020 --> 00:04:00.170
is the "Harry Potter
Cursed Child" soundtrack.

00:04:00.170 --> 00:04:04.610
We're going to see a quick video
introducing that album, which

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:05.570
has just been released.

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:09.554
[MUSIC - IMOGEN HEAP, "GODRIC'S
 HOLLOW"]

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:47.910
IMOGEN HEAP: That is a bit of
the play, which is on Broadway,

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:50.590
which is wonderful.

00:04:50.590 --> 00:04:54.960
Yeah, for about four years
ago, I got a call from a friend

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:57.900
called Steven Hoggett, who
is a movement director,

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:01.830
and he used to have this group
called The Frantic Assembly.

00:05:01.830 --> 00:05:05.203
And when I released--
well, just after I released

00:05:05.203 --> 00:05:07.120
a song, an album, called
"Speak for Yourself,"

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.540
which is the same album that
I couldn't finish that song,

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:13.560
and I released it by
myself with my own label

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:16.530
and eventually
licensed it to Sony

00:05:16.530 --> 00:05:20.650
because I couldn't do
with all the mail orders.

00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:24.120
But before that, I got this call
from this guy, Steven Hoggett

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.802
back then, like 20, 15
years ago, and he's like--

00:05:26.802 --> 00:05:28.260
are these annoying
you, by the way?

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:28.927
[RATTLING SOUND]

00:05:28.927 --> 00:05:29.481
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:29.481 --> 00:05:30.720
Or should I take them off?

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.070
Are they present?

00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:33.540
No?

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:35.910
Because they're
really annoying me.

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:39.617
Anyway, so yeah, he was like,
I love this album "Speak

00:05:39.617 --> 00:05:40.200
for Yourself."

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.940
Could I-- I want to put it in
this play that I'm working on,

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:44.760
and there's going to be
people dancing around to it.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:46.390
And I was like, OK,
that sounds really good,

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:47.670
and I didn't ask
him for payment.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:49.253
And I was just like,
that sounds good.

00:05:49.253 --> 00:05:50.910
Yeah, OK, here you
go, and I tweaked

00:05:50.910 --> 00:05:53.640
some things I made it a bit
longer, and that kind of stuff.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:55.490
And then it went into this
play, and it was really great,

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:56.140
and I loved it.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:59.310
It was the first time I'd
seen live dance to my music,

00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:02.290
and I really enjoyed it, but
I didn't ask for payment.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:04.698
But if I had been signed to
a major label at the time,

00:06:04.698 --> 00:06:06.323
they would've been
like, uh, yes, we're

00:06:06.323 --> 00:06:08.670
going to spend a whole year
discussing how much she

00:06:08.670 --> 00:06:10.140
should get for
this, and then you

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:11.432
won't be able to use it anyway.

00:06:11.432 --> 00:06:13.590
Aha.

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:17.740
So I basically-- yeah,
it was really great.

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:20.850
And then we made friends,
and we kept in touch,

00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:23.520
and then he did all
these amazing things.

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:27.190
And then the next-- not the next
call, but a call four years ago

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:31.410
was him saying, hi, Imogen,
or Immy, as he calls me,

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:33.443
working on this play,
and I can't really

00:06:33.443 --> 00:06:34.860
tell you what it's
about, but they

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:37.125
love your music
and all this stuff

00:06:37.125 --> 00:06:39.000
because I did all this
weird orchestral stuff

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.140
and a capella, strange
stuff for an accompaniment

00:06:43.140 --> 00:06:44.900
for an old silent movie.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:47.820
And nobody ever gets to hear
that stuff, but he loves me,

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:49.620
and he loves all
of my music, and he

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:51.310
knows it all really well.

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:53.370
And so he was putting
all these random bits

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:56.550
in there, which hardly anyone's
heard, and it felt really good.

00:06:56.550 --> 00:06:58.350
And he was like, I
think they really just

00:06:58.350 --> 00:07:00.330
want you to make the music.

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:02.395
And I was like, who is it?

00:07:02.395 --> 00:07:04.020
And he said, I can't
tell you, but it's

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:05.213
about a boy with a scar.

00:07:05.213 --> 00:07:05.880
And I was like--

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:07.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:09.880
--OK, that's a bit
of a give away.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:12.432
And so I looked up online,
and I saw his name connected

00:07:12.432 --> 00:07:13.890
to this creative
team who'd already

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:15.390
announced they're doing a play.

00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:18.700
And then I was like,
that's exciting.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:20.782
So then, yeah, I
met up with Sonia,

00:07:20.782 --> 00:07:24.370
who's-- she's the producer,
and they offered me the job.

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:28.770
And yeah, life took a
very different turn.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:29.435
Yeah.

00:07:29.435 --> 00:07:31.560
BEN ARTHUR: What was your
relationship to the Harry

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:34.200
Potter universe before that?

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:38.220
IMOGEN HEAP: Thin,
quite distant.

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:40.910
I really don't like
reading very much.

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:41.910
I mean, that's not true.

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:45.790
I like the information
that's in the book.

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:49.680
I just don't like the process
of actually reading it,

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.320
and I've never enjoyed that.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:55.110
My dad thinks that if
it wasn't down to him

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:57.840
kind of showing
me, going through,

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:00.690
he thinks I'm
dyslexic, and maybe

00:08:00.690 --> 00:08:05.700
because I really struggle
getting the words in my head.

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:08.370
Maybe that's why I
like making my own.

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:14.390
So anyway, so yeah, so that's
how it ended up in there, and--

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:17.310
BEN ARTHUR: Fascinating,
and if I can ask,

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:22.590
for those of us who were much,
much deeper into that universe,

00:08:22.590 --> 00:08:25.200
can we fanboy and fangirl
out for a second and ask,

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.000
did you hang out
with JK Rowling?

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.890
Did she invite you
to her house, which

00:08:28.890 --> 00:08:31.620
I assume is a magical
castle that you can only

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:34.919
access by a unicorn or a
magical boat or something?

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:39.080
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah, I did meet
the lady herself a few times.

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:42.030
Yeah, she was on
set quite a lot,

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:46.828
and yeah, she's was
very nice to me.

00:08:46.828 --> 00:08:49.120
She says-- she actually, I
think, when I first met her,

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:50.550
she did this to me.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:53.300
And I was like--

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:57.720
no, she's very happy because
I discovered that they really

00:08:57.720 --> 00:09:01.740
wanted somebody British,
a composer that's British

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.058
and that was a woman.

00:09:04.058 --> 00:09:05.850
BEN ARTHUR: So I was
never in the running--

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:07.683
IMOGEN HEAP: There's
not that many you can--

00:09:07.683 --> 00:09:09.630
BEN ARTHUR: --really at all.

00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:12.090
IMOGEN HEAP: I think also
with the help of Steven,

00:09:12.090 --> 00:09:14.630
and the fact that the director
and him are best buddies,

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:15.840
it all it all helped.

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:19.490
BEN ARTHUR: So can you tell
us about the creative process?

00:09:19.490 --> 00:09:20.555
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah.

00:09:20.555 --> 00:09:23.100
BEN ARTHUR: Because as
I've heard you describe it,

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:26.070
sort of it's a creative process
within a creative process

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:28.517
because they're working
on their own thing.

00:09:28.517 --> 00:09:29.850
IMOGEN HEAP: Is that your phone?

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:31.360
BEN ARTHUR: It's
really awful, isn't it.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:32.152
IMOGEN HEAP: Roger!

00:09:32.152 --> 00:09:33.670
BEN ARTHUR: Embarrassing.

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:34.170
Ben.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:35.628
IMOGEN HEAP: Your
name's not Roger.

00:09:35.628 --> 00:09:36.814
Your name's Ben.

00:09:36.814 --> 00:09:37.640
Who's Roger?

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:38.460
I just-- somebody called Roger.

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:39.440
BEN ARTHUR: You can
absolutely call me--

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:39.820
IMOGEN HEAP: It's
very confusing.

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:40.380
BEN ARTHUR: --Roger, though.

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:41.645
It's completely fine.

00:09:41.645 --> 00:09:43.720
IMOGEN HEAP: Oh
well, now we're even.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:46.450
You have your phone, and
I called the wrong name.

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:51.170
So Ben, Ben Arthur,
your question was--

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:53.097
what was your question?

00:09:53.097 --> 00:09:54.430
Oh, the creative process, sorry.

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:57.280
Yeah, so the
creative process was

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:00.500
they really liked a lot
of existing material,

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:02.710
but they needed it
adapted, but they had--

00:10:02.710 --> 00:10:05.260
It's a five hour play, and
they wanted a lot of it

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:08.072
to be music underscored,
but they also--

00:10:08.072 --> 00:10:10.030
there's kind of three
different types of music.

00:10:10.030 --> 00:10:11.632
There's music that
they interact with,

00:10:11.632 --> 00:10:13.090
which is when
they're on the stage,

00:10:13.090 --> 00:10:14.715
and they're moving
around to the music.

00:10:14.715 --> 00:10:17.200
There's the underscore, and
then there's scene changes,

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:22.780
like a wall goes across, and
it's like-- (SINGING) Ha--

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:24.320
and things like that.

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:27.003
And so the underscore
bit is quite a lot

00:10:27.003 --> 00:10:29.170
of existing material that
just kind of bumbling away

00:10:29.170 --> 00:10:30.850
in the background
that's been adapted,

00:10:30.850 --> 00:10:32.890
and stretched, and
added different things,

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:34.960
and lots of high
frequencies taken out

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:38.020
because it kind of gets
in the way of talking.

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:40.270
So I learned a lot about
how to sculpt around

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:44.590
the vocal human voice area.

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:50.710
And then a lot of, yeah,
drones, lots of vocal-- loads

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:51.580
of vocalizations.

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:52.747
There's no lyrics, actually.

00:10:52.747 --> 00:10:54.363
There's only one bit
that has a lyric.

00:10:54.363 --> 00:10:56.530
BEN ARTHUR: Indeed, that's
from "Hide and and Seek."

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:57.730
IMOGEN HEAP: Of course.

00:10:57.730 --> 00:11:00.230
They had to put my
famous song in there.

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:03.700
So that's the one song they
really wanted with a lyric,

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.280
and I didn't want to--

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:07.240
it didn't feel right
to have me singing it,

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:09.198
and they did want to have
me singing it anyway,

00:11:09.198 --> 00:11:11.800
so I got my friend's
choir to sing it,

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:14.770
and then I kind of added
the vocal layers underneath

00:11:14.770 --> 00:11:17.090
and made nice drones.

00:11:17.090 --> 00:11:20.440
But most of the time, it was
all about the transitions,

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:22.080
and that was really, really fun.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:24.820
It really tested my
theory skills to,

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:26.290
like, how do I
get from that key?

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:29.530
How do I modulate from there to
there, and how do I, you know,

00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:30.587
do this?

00:11:30.587 --> 00:11:32.170
So there's a lot of
existing material.

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:35.560
And very luckily,
over the years I've

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:40.330
been quite vigilant into making
sure that all of the songs

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:43.120
have their stems, and they're
all documented, and kind of

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:44.270
filed quite nicely.

00:11:44.270 --> 00:11:48.160
So all of the songs from
"Speak for Yourself" up all

00:11:48.160 --> 00:11:51.870
have drums, strings, vocals,
backup vocals, effects, blah,

00:11:51.870 --> 00:11:55.200
blah, blah, weird sounds,
arpeggiated things, et cetera,

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:56.248
et cetera.

00:11:56.248 --> 00:11:57.790
And then, so I was
lucky enough to be

00:11:57.790 --> 00:12:00.123
able to pull that in, and
those ones that I hadn't done,

00:12:00.123 --> 00:12:02.770
I've got this awesome
assistant called Alexi,

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:06.280
and he was in my studio back
in Engla-- back in this village

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:07.080
where we live.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:10.870
And he would be kind of
getting those together and then

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:13.840
dropping them into Dropbox
into Ableton sessions,

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:17.300
where then I was seated in the
theater for about three months.

00:12:17.300 --> 00:12:21.160
And just with my little
computer and my little drive

00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:24.370
and whatever, and
had my microphone,

00:12:24.370 --> 00:12:26.440
and some little toys.

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:28.590
And then I was just there
like that the whole time.

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.340
And my only regret is
that I didn't really

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:33.430
get to talk it to anyone
other than, did you like that?

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:36.490
Or could you make that
a bit more like this?

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:39.000
Or could you make it a bit less?

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.610
And yeah, so I didn't really get
to talk to the gang very much,

00:12:42.610 --> 00:12:46.180
and I was literally there
from 10:00 in the morning

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:48.745
until 11:00 at night, and I
was always-- well, not always,

00:12:48.745 --> 00:12:50.120
but I was quite
a lot of the time

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:55.840
the last one in there saying
hi to the security guard.

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:58.840
BEN ARTHUR: And you took all of
this music, something like 100

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:02.860
cues, and created an album?

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:03.610
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah.

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:04.900
BEN ARTHUR: Sort of
a cohesive album--

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:06.358
what was that
process like for you?

00:13:06.358 --> 00:13:07.942
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah,
so in the theater,

00:13:07.942 --> 00:13:09.400
it was really great
because there's

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:14.130
tons of inputs to kind of
react against and be like,

00:13:14.130 --> 00:13:16.318
oh, that sound works
beautifully with the light.

00:13:16.318 --> 00:13:18.610
Oh, that sound goes beautifully
with the sound effects,

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:20.420
or ah, the pace of that person.

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.307
So all of these are
kind of affirmations

00:13:22.307 --> 00:13:23.140
that that's working.

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:23.765
That's working.

00:13:23.765 --> 00:13:25.810
Keep going, which you
don't get in the studio

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:28.360
when you're all by yourself.

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:31.160
But at the same time, because
it's a big theater system,

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:33.758
and you don't hear a lot
of the detail in the mix,

00:13:33.758 --> 00:13:35.800
so it's kind of getting
away with murder in terms

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:38.060
of what I could mix in
the time that I had,

00:13:38.060 --> 00:13:41.220
which is 2 and 1/2 hours of
music that, quite a lot of it

00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:43.610
done also from scratch.

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:46.820
And so when I finally took
that back into my studio,

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.940
it was like, oh my goodness.

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:50.950
I've got so much work to do.

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:52.870
There's a gazillion
pops, and clicks,

00:13:52.870 --> 00:13:55.420
and all kinds of things
I had to draw out.

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:58.210
And then just making
it sound lush,

00:13:58.210 --> 00:14:00.310
and beautiful, and
layered, and giving it

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:04.190
the attention that I do to
my own records, but to--

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:05.980
well, it's a 78 minute album.

00:14:05.980 --> 00:14:10.190
It's like as much as I could
fit on a CD physically possible,

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:11.860
and it's 42 tracks.

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:14.920
And so it goes into
four acts, and they're

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:17.650
like one long piece of music for
20 minutes, another long piece

00:14:17.650 --> 00:14:19.330
of music for 20
minutes, but it's

00:14:19.330 --> 00:14:21.640
going through 14 or
15 keys, so that's

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:24.850
where the kind of, how do you
get from this key to that key

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:27.040
into 3/4 from 7/8,
duh, duh, duh.

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:29.950
But it's really fun, but
it's a lot of hard work.

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:34.120
And I did most of it
standing up because I also

00:14:34.120 --> 00:14:37.510
had a life at that time
in a flat in London,

00:14:37.510 --> 00:14:40.000
and so there's a lot
of it just standing up.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.440
But that was quite
good for my posture.

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:44.617
BEN ARTHUR: Excellent.

00:14:44.617 --> 00:14:45.700
A personal recommendation.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:48.220
I've been listening to
the album for a while now.

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:50.980
Walking through the city and
listening to that on headphones

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:54.732
gives you a very weird
magical layer of New York

00:14:54.732 --> 00:14:55.690
that-- very surprising.

00:14:55.690 --> 00:14:55.891
IMOGEN HEAP: Oh, that's

00:14:55.891 --> 00:14:56.440
BEN ARTHUR: Cool.

00:14:56.440 --> 00:14:58.110
Because you did a wonderful
job sort of making--

00:14:58.110 --> 00:14:58.943
IMOGEN HEAP: Thanks.

00:14:58.943 --> 00:15:00.660
BEN ARTHUR: --that feel magical.

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:01.410
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah.

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:02.020
BEN ARTHUR: --which.

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:04.520
IMOGEN HEAP: There were certain
sounds that I always kind of

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:05.830
were drawn to.

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:09.190
Kind of the other
kind of secret weapon

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:12.970
I had was I developed
with a company

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:16.810
called Soniccouture my own set
of virtual instruments of all

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:20.020
my favorite sounds in my studio
so that I could basically

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:21.400
take them on the road with me.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:22.780
So I could have my mbira.

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:24.872
I could have my cello,
like harmonic stuff.

00:15:24.872 --> 00:15:26.080
I could have my cocktail kit.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:27.900
I could have my whirlies.

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:29.560
BEN ARTHUR: Your
marxophone, I read.

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:30.340
IMOGEN HEAP: My marxophone.

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:31.000
BEN ARTHUR: Which is a--

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:31.510
IMOGEN HEAP: My [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:33.570
BEN ARTHUR: --sort of
socialist trumpet, I think.

00:15:33.570 --> 00:15:34.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:34.070 --> 00:15:37.510
IMOGEN HEAP: No, it's
a bit like an autoharp,

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:40.810
but it has twangs on it.

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:43.150
I don't know what
you're thinking of.

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:44.810
So yeah, a marxophone.

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:45.540
I see, right.

00:15:45.540 --> 00:15:47.140
I'm a bit slow today.

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:52.200
Anyway, so cut that bit out.

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:53.500
Yeah, so I have this--

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:56.410
we call it the box of tricks,
which is quite funny because it

00:15:56.410 --> 00:16:00.220
ends up being a box of tricks
in a magical theater piece.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:04.900
And I used all of those
sounds to basically make

00:16:04.900 --> 00:16:08.830
things sound like me, so I
would always use the marxophone,

00:16:08.830 --> 00:16:10.330
and I'd use the "choir of mes."

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:12.910
I could play "choirs
of me" on my--

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:14.230
I had sampled my voice.

00:16:14.230 --> 00:16:16.730
So if anyone wants to make a
song that sounds a bit like me,

00:16:16.730 --> 00:16:18.397
you just find the box
of tricks and just

00:16:18.397 --> 00:16:21.140
go, la la, a bit of
marxophone, a bit of string,

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:24.115
bit of vocal harmony
things, and some--

00:16:24.115 --> 00:16:26.050
BEN ARTHUR: So speaking
of instruments,

00:16:26.050 --> 00:16:28.720
I wanted to turn to
the Mi.Mu gloves.

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:32.530
We've got a quick little video
to introduce you all to this

00:16:32.530 --> 00:16:35.670
if you haven't seen it
before, and here she goes.

00:16:35.670 --> 00:16:39.590
[MUSIC - IMOGEN HEAP, "JUST FOR
 NOW"]

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.069
IMOGEN HEAP: OK, that was
really not a very good example

00:17:24.069 --> 00:17:24.810
because--

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:25.089
BEN ARTHUR: Thank you.

00:17:25.089 --> 00:17:26.547
IMOGEN HEAP: What
happened before--

00:17:26.547 --> 00:17:28.580
It's not your fault.
It's not your fault.

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:31.530
I think it was my team who
some reason gave you that.

00:17:31.530 --> 00:17:36.010
But basically, yeah, what I'd
done previous to that is I'd

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:39.400
looped my voice by
catching my voice,

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:42.040
and then it would
create a loop, and then

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:43.510
I would catch another loop.

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:45.250
Well, I'd actually
put that aside,

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:46.960
and then I would
catch another loop,

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:48.150
and then I'd put
that aside, and then

00:17:48.150 --> 00:17:50.025
I'd catch another loop,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:17:50.025 --> 00:17:55.030
And what I'm doing is I'm going,
posture, first up is record.

00:17:55.030 --> 00:17:59.555
And when I'm out of that
zone, it goes to play,

00:17:59.555 --> 00:18:01.180
or when it goes to
this zone, it plays.

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:02.595
And then it continues to play.

00:18:02.595 --> 00:18:03.970
And then I can't
remember exactly

00:18:03.970 --> 00:18:06.040
because that was
ages ago, but it's

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:07.810
something like when
I want to pull up

00:18:07.810 --> 00:18:09.400
the volume of the
first loop, then

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:11.442
I would use my finger like
this, and I would just

00:18:11.442 --> 00:18:13.900
be like, up, down, up,
or just go straight up.

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:20.332
It would be 120, 127 in MIDI
note, but like 100% loudness.

00:18:20.332 --> 00:18:21.790
And then if I wanted
to add reverb,

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:24.100
I just used my secret
finger posture,

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:29.650
which basically activates
the reverb fader,

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:32.170
or like the pop in my software.

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:35.810
And it just says
from 0% to 100%.

00:18:35.810 --> 00:18:39.340
So if I was like, dong,
you just sound like now.

00:18:39.340 --> 00:18:41.896
But if I was over there,
it would be like dooong,

00:18:41.896 --> 00:18:44.710
as if I was in a massive cave.

00:18:44.710 --> 00:18:47.920
And then yeah, so I
would play bass lines,

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:49.540
or I might play twinkly sounds.

00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:54.720
Or it's just things that I
do anyway when I perform.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:57.278
Previously, you
kind of have to be

00:18:57.278 --> 00:18:59.820
kind of a little bit barricaded
by gear if you want to sample

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:04.270
stuff, or you're locked into the
physical nature of whatever box

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:08.170
you're using, and the
gloves are basically

00:19:08.170 --> 00:19:09.610
controllers at your fingertips.

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:14.230
And you can just be very
expressive to something

00:19:14.230 --> 00:19:16.510
which is quite boring,
actually, in real life.

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:20.010
It's just like, turn up a thing
to 100%, and it's like it,

00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:23.330
eh, but you could do
that really expressively,

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:26.650
like yeah or
something like that.

00:19:26.650 --> 00:19:30.720
But this is much more like, oh,
she's making her voice bigger,

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:32.350
or she's catching
her voice, and now

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:34.753
she's moving it left
or right, or maybe even

00:19:34.753 --> 00:19:36.670
in surround, which I'm
doing on the tour, kind

00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:39.310
of moving it around a 3D space.

00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:43.820
And then just kind of sampling
my voice, bringing in the coda,

00:19:43.820 --> 00:19:46.870
harmonizers so I can
harmonize with my voice.

00:19:46.870 --> 00:19:50.710
Sometimes I integrate it
with an IR camera-- well,

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:52.780
they don't make them
anymore, but a connect,

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:54.893
and I would map the stage
into different zones

00:19:54.893 --> 00:19:56.560
so I could be like,
when I'm over there,

00:19:56.560 --> 00:20:01.630
then make the drums more sparse.

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:03.820
And when I'm back here,
make them more frenetic.

00:20:03.820 --> 00:20:06.840
Or when I'm over there,
switch my harmonizer to minor,

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:08.020
or when I'm over here.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:10.540
Or when I'm in the middle,
take out my harmonizer.

00:20:10.540 --> 00:20:15.310
So using the stage
spatially to effect

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:21.040
the kind of bigger parameters in
change in a system like Ableton

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:23.000
or [INAUDIBLE] whatever.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.840
So it's basically like a
mapping device, but how it feels

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:30.340
is you take on the physicality
of something which doesn't

00:20:30.340 --> 00:20:33.430
have a physical representation.

00:20:33.430 --> 00:20:38.630
It's like a filter or
a bunch of effects.

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:40.723
It doesn't have a thing.

00:20:40.723 --> 00:20:41.890
It's not like a bass guitar.

00:20:41.890 --> 00:20:43.840
It's like, ah,
that's a bass guitar.

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.440
It's like a reverb, so
you become the reverb,

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:51.070
and you become the
mixing desk, and you

00:20:51.070 --> 00:20:55.040
become the multiple voices or--

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:58.690
Yeah, the only downside that
I've discovered from it,

00:20:58.690 --> 00:21:02.660
other than lots of
programming to kind of get it

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:06.280
so it feels really human, so
you're never even thinking

00:21:06.280 --> 00:21:08.620
about, actually, I'm going
to bring in my reverb now.

00:21:08.620 --> 00:21:09.828
I'm going to sample my voice.

00:21:09.828 --> 00:21:11.870
It just becomes second nature.

00:21:11.870 --> 00:21:14.370
I'm going to record my voice,
going to make it a bit bigger.

00:21:14.370 --> 00:21:16.260
Now I'm going to add some har--

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:16.840
some delays.

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:19.720
You kind of create a gestural
language the more and more you

00:21:19.720 --> 00:21:21.790
use the system
because it, obviously,

00:21:21.790 --> 00:21:24.410
has a bit of software between--
they're called Glover--

00:21:24.410 --> 00:21:26.320
which you could also
add other inputs.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:29.110
So you don't have to use
the gloves with Glover.

00:21:29.110 --> 00:21:29.967
You can use--

00:21:29.967 --> 00:21:31.050
Yeah, you can use connect.

00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:32.050
You can use [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:32.050 --> 00:21:33.360
You can use an iphone.

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.860
You can use Leap Motion.

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:38.890
You can use whatever,
other types of inputs.

00:21:38.890 --> 00:21:43.600
And then use them to move around
things in Ableton or whatever.

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.610
So the gloves are
essentially just trying

00:21:45.610 --> 00:21:49.780
to get away from
this limited space I

00:21:49.780 --> 00:21:53.200
felt of trying to add
lots more gear to create

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:57.130
a fluidity or a kind of
spontaneity on the stage.

00:21:57.130 --> 00:21:59.560
BEN ARTHUR: Sure, and for
you, now that you've actually

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:02.110
developed these,
do you find when

00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:04.600
you perform that
you're in them most

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:06.110
of the time, all of the time?

00:22:06.110 --> 00:22:07.630
IMOGEN HEAP: Yeah, I
wear them all the time--

00:22:07.630 --> 00:22:08.020
BEN ARTHUR: All the time.

00:22:08.020 --> 00:22:10.460
IMOGEN HEAP: --on the stage
because why take them off?

00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:13.950
They're quite pretty, and
they don't itch or anything.

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:15.820
They basically have
eight bend sensors.

00:22:15.820 --> 00:22:18.250
They've got 1, 2, 2, 2, and 1.

00:22:18.250 --> 00:22:20.132
They have lights for
feedback, and you

00:22:20.132 --> 00:22:22.090
can program the lights
to do whatever you want.

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:24.130
You might be like, turn
it red when I'm in record,

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:26.050
which you know it's in record,
but it's nice for the audience

00:22:26.050 --> 00:22:27.175
to see, oh, it's in record.

00:22:27.175 --> 00:22:28.930
It's gone red.

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:30.290
And then it's got a battery.

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:33.910
It's got an IMU so that you
can get your positional data,

00:22:33.910 --> 00:22:38.710
and it's got an accelerometer,
so you can be like, drum peaks.

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:42.600
And I do air guitar as
well, which is really fun.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:46.322
And yeah, so that kind
of combination-- then

00:22:46.322 --> 00:22:48.280
you've got your axes, so
you've got your pitch.

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:50.110
You've got yaw, and
you've got roll.

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:52.210
And then you've got
different zones--

00:22:52.210 --> 00:22:53.800
backwards, forwards, up, down.

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:57.030
And the combination of that
leads to so many possibilities

00:22:57.030 --> 00:22:59.030
because if you have a
keyboard, and you're like,

00:22:59.030 --> 00:23:00.670
I'm going to play a
squidgy bass sound.

00:23:00.670 --> 00:23:02.500
So you might be like,
dum, dum, dum, dum.

00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:05.140
And you want it to go--
woo, woo, wow or something.

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:06.473
You could do that with pressure.

00:23:06.473 --> 00:23:07.848
You could make it
slightly harder

00:23:07.848 --> 00:23:09.170
if you want it to go, wow.

00:23:09.170 --> 00:23:12.820
But if you want it to do
that and change the tone

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:15.640
or something around
it, you would

00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:18.640
have to use your other hand,
which is then entirely consumed

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:20.248
by going wow.

00:23:20.248 --> 00:23:22.540
And you're suddenly just
playing a three note bass line

00:23:22.540 --> 00:23:24.550
with a wow thing,
but you could just

00:23:24.550 --> 00:23:28.320
be going, wow like that the
same, but just your whole hand,

00:23:28.320 --> 00:23:31.180
and you could move
around the stage and do.

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:33.525
