00:38:45.270 --> 00:38:47.580
imagination of the future,
but the Creative Passport

00:38:47.580 --> 00:38:48.400
is a thing.

00:38:48.400 --> 00:38:52.883
It's like an app, a trust
anchor for other services

00:38:52.883 --> 00:38:55.425
to be able to go, oh, yeah, that
is Imogen Heap because she's

00:38:55.425 --> 00:38:56.842
got a Creative
Passport, and she's

00:38:56.842 --> 00:38:59.050
been verified by her
peers, blah, blah, blah.

00:38:59.050 --> 00:39:01.650
So if you wanted to
go and book a gig,

00:39:01.650 --> 00:39:04.080
some promoter could
pretty much trust you

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:06.780
because you've been
verified by your peers,

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:09.430
and you have a good track
record, and that kind of thing.

00:39:09.430 --> 00:39:12.690
So at the moment,
where the record ind--

00:39:12.690 --> 00:39:14.970
the majors are going
to get interested is

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:17.980
when this database
does start to emerge,

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:20.335
which it is starting to
emerge in places like Sweden.

00:39:20.335 --> 00:39:21.210
There's one in Malta.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:21.730
There's one--

00:39:21.730 --> 00:39:23.313
And actually, here
there's going to be

00:39:23.313 --> 00:39:26.130
a new one around the
Music Modernization Act,

00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:28.058
around the mechanicals,
how they're

00:39:28.058 --> 00:39:29.850
going to be paid to
the writers, and that's

00:39:29.850 --> 00:39:32.460
something that just passed a
few months ago in Congress.

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:34.620
So they have to build that
in the next two years,

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:38.580
and I'm going, hello,
IBM and Berkeley.

00:39:38.580 --> 00:39:41.640
How are you going to do that
without the music makers?

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:43.800
How are you going to
build that without us

00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:46.878
being able to add to the
content that you have

00:39:46.878 --> 00:39:48.420
around your publishers
because that's

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:49.050
how they're going to build it.

00:39:49.050 --> 00:39:52.200
They're going to combine the big
publishers together and create

00:39:52.200 --> 00:39:55.110
another database, but it's
only going to be as good

00:39:55.110 --> 00:39:59.440
as their combined
databases, and it won't--

00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:01.800
The problem with that is
that, whether they're guilty

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:05.400
or they're not, the money that
comes in from the services

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:08.508
will then go to
this body, and then

00:40:08.508 --> 00:40:10.800
the money that can't be
distributed, because they don't

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:12.800
know the writers, because
they're too small fry,

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:14.970
and it's too much effort
for them to do it,

00:40:14.970 --> 00:40:18.030
will just go back to the
writers that they do have.

00:40:18.030 --> 00:40:20.670
They do look after, after four
years or whatever the deal is.

00:40:20.670 --> 00:40:23.100
It's probably
something like that.

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:26.100
It will get redistributed
back to the original writers

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:28.860
that they look after, so
the other writers are all

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:30.510
around the world,
